The new anti-globalization backlash
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of world's leading developed economies' leaders, no one can predict which of them will be the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has lasted for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be towards convergence and people appeared to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking the stores of this chain became a standard form of protest against globalization.
But lately, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand less about foreigners.
In response to the evolving consumer preferences (which are now increasingly sophisticated), companies are shifting their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared being inundated by Japanese cars, and they then began producing these cars domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are made in the United States. But the reversal of merchandise globalization is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotics engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, the current criticism of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution reflects not only the slowdown in trade growth.
Rich country consumers are much more comfortable with foreign products, and in some cases even dependent on them, from constantly updated electronics and cheap "fast fashion," which has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, today's opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protections in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on the issues of opaque tribunals protecting foreign companies' interests and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
Then there is the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, anxiety about this influx may be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are populations in advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
This is not to say that they have never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people worldwide head each year to advanced countries.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we tend more towards quick and superficial experiences rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper understanding or cooperation.
A continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are reluctant to provide good or simply honest service to people who are surely never coming back.
Restaurants serve food without a smile that is mediocre (or worse), taxi drivers rip you off, hoteliers lie about their amenities.
In addition, this little game can experience interruptions.
On sites where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it also becomes a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to trigger deep economic destabilization.
Tourism businesses respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The symbol of modern tourism is a giant cruise ship where passengers can spend a few hours at each stop (to visit a beautiful Caribbean island or an old Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean cruise ship, Harmony of the Seas, aims to recreate all climates of the world.
In fact, this more than 30-meter-long ship, which contains the Eiffel Tower within it, has a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Bus and train tour companies do the same, ensuring their clients' safety by releasing them at famous sites for a limited time, just long enough to take a few photos.
This style of travel places a constraint on local infrastructure capacity.
There is often not enough space for walking along Venice's canals or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meeting only scammers who offer trinkets or extremely expensive taxi rides.
The locals do not appreciate the groups of tourists who gather around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor does anyone maintain any trust relationships.
It's easy to feel some nostalgia for a time when tourism went hand in hand with long stays and longer-term encounters with very different cultures.
Of course, it would be impossible, given the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or months at a time in old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Might world leaders participate in summits like the G-7 by living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
Soon after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill famously packed up and moved into the White House for 24 days to consolidate the Atlantic alliance between Great Britain and the United States, deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the populists' greatest enemy among globalists.
